Here is the same quantity with **all “ ∞ ’’s written as honest limits**.

---

### 1 Start from the ε-version we already had  
\[
d_I[\mu_\infty](x)-d_I[\mu_{t(\varepsilon)}](x)
\;=\;
2\lim_{\varepsilon\downarrow0}\;
   \varepsilon\,\partial_\varepsilon
   \log\!\left(
      \frac{e^{\varepsilon\Delta}\mu_\infty}
           {e^{\varepsilon\Delta}\mu_{t(\varepsilon)}}
   \right)\!(x).
\tag{A}
\]

---

### 2 Replace the logarithm by the explicit time–integral *with a limit*  
\[
\log\!\left(
      \frac{e^{\varepsilon\Delta}\mu_\infty}
           {e^{\varepsilon\Delta}\mu_{t(\varepsilon)}}
   \right)(x)
   \;=\;
\lim_{T\to\infty}\;
   \int_{t(\varepsilon)}^{T}
      \partial_s\log\!\bigl(e^{\varepsilon\Delta}\mu_s\bigr)(x)\;ds.
\]

Insert this into (A):

\[
\boxed{%
d_I[\mu_\infty](x)-d_I[\mu_{t(\varepsilon)}](x)
\;=\;
2\lim_{\varepsilon\downarrow0}\;
   \varepsilon\,\partial_\varepsilon
   \Bigl[
      \lim_{T\to\infty}
      \int_{t(\varepsilon)}^{T}
         \partial_s\log\!\bigl(e^{\varepsilon\Delta}\mu_s\bigr)(x)\;ds
   \Bigr]}.
\tag{B}
\]

---

### 3 After changing variables to time \(t\)  
If \(t=t(\varepsilon)\) is strictly monotone with inverse \(\varepsilon=\varepsilon(t)\) and  
\(C(t):=\varepsilon(t)\,dt/d\varepsilon(t)\), then

\[
\boxed{%
d_I[\mu_\infty](x)-d_I[\mu_t](x)
\;=\;
2\lim_{t\to\infty}
   C(t)\;
   \lim_{T\to\infty}
      \int_{t}^{T}
         \partial_s\log\!\bigl(e^{\varepsilon(s)\Delta}\mu_s\bigr)(x)\;ds}.
\tag{C}
\]

---

Equation (C) is the sought-for form: **an outer limit \(t\to\infty\)** (from trading ε for \(t\)) and an **inner limit \(T\to\infty\)** that makes the time-integral explicit and finite at every stage.

\[
\boxed{\;
\lim_{t\to\infty}\!\bigl[d_I[\mu_\infty](x)-d_I[\mu_t](x)\bigr]
\;=\;
2\lim_{t\to\infty}\!
      \Bigl[\varepsilon(t)\,\tfrac{dt}{d\varepsilon}(t)\Bigr]\,
      \lim_{T\to\infty}
          \int_{t}^{T}
              \partial_s
              \log\!\bigl(e^{\varepsilon(s)\Delta}\mu_s\bigr)(x)\;ds
\;}
\]

Write the local-dimension gap with **both limits shown explicitly** and keep the smoothing scale fixed at the outer time \(t\):

\[
\boxed{%
\lim_{t\to\infty}
\Bigl[d_I[\mu_\infty](x)\;-\;d_I[\mu_t](x)\Bigr]
\;=\;
2\;\lim_{t\to\infty}
\Bigl(\varepsilon(t)\,\tfrac{dt}{d\varepsilon}(t)\Bigr)
\;\lim_{T\to\infty}
        \int_{s=t}^{T}
               \partial_s\,
               \log\!\bigl(e^{\varepsilon(t)\,\Delta}\mu_s\bigr)(x)\;ds
}
\]

Here  

* \(\displaystyle \varepsilon(t)\) is the chosen scale-time schedule (e.g. \(e^{-\lambda t}\) or \(t^{-\alpha}\)); it depends only on the **outer** variable \(t\) and **does not vary** with the integration dummy \(s\).  
* \(\displaystyle \varepsilon(t)\,\tfrac{dt}{d\varepsilon}(t)\) is the finite prefactor \(C(t)\) that arose from switching the limit parameter from \(\varepsilon\) to \(t\).

Stop here.

Define the **error term**

\[
\boxed{\;
\eta(x)
\;:=\;
2\,
\varepsilon(t)\,\frac{dt}{d\varepsilon}(t)\;
\lim_{T\to\infty}
      \int_{s=t}^{T}
             \partial_s\,
             \log\bigl(e^{\varepsilon(t)\,\Delta}\mu_s\bigr)(x)\;ds
\;}
\qquad\bigl(t\text{ large}\bigr).
\]

The left-hand side that previously involved  
\(\displaystyle\lim_{t\to\infty}\!\bigl[d_I[\mu_\infty](x)-d_I[\mu_t](x)\bigr]\)  
has been dropped, and the entire right-hand expression is now denoted \(\eta(x)\).

Because \(\varepsilon(t)\) is **held fixed while the \(s\)-derivative is taken**, only the measure \(\mu_{s}\) carries \(s\)-dependence.  With the Liouville equation
\[
\partial_{s}\mu_{s}\;=\;-\mathcal L_{f}\mu_{s},
\qquad
\mathcal L_{f}:=\nabla\!\cdot\!(f\,\cdot)\;,
\]
one has
\[
\partial_{s}\,\log\!\bigl(e^{\varepsilon(t)\Delta}\mu_{s}\bigr)(x)
\;=\;
\frac{\partial_{s}\bigl(e^{\varepsilon(t)\Delta}\mu_{s}\bigr)(x)}
     {e^{\varepsilon(t)\Delta}\mu_{s}(x)}
\;=\;
-\,
\frac{e^{\varepsilon(t)\Delta}\!\bigl(\mathcal L_{f}\mu_{s}\bigr)(x)}
     {e^{\varepsilon(t)\Delta}\mu_{s}(x)}.
\]

Equivalently, using \(e^{\varepsilon(t)\Delta}\mathcal L_{f}
      =\mathcal L_{f}e^{\varepsilon(t)\Delta}
        +[\,e^{\varepsilon(t)\Delta},\mathcal L_{f}\,]\),

\[
\partial_{s}\,\log\!\bigl(e^{\varepsilon(t)\Delta}\mu_{s}\bigr)(x)
\;=\;
-\,
\frac{\mathcal L_{f}\bigl(e^{\varepsilon(t)\Delta}\mu_{s}\bigr)(x)}
     {e^{\varepsilon(t)\Delta}\mu_{s}(x)}
\;-\,
\frac{\bigl[\,e^{\varepsilon(t)\Delta},\mathcal L_{f}\,\bigr]\mu_{s}(x)}
     {e^{\varepsilon(t)\Delta}\mu_{s}(x)}.
\]

This is the explicit form to substitute inside the integral defining \(\eta(x)\).
